  "prompt": "Why doesn't Amazon start a courier business?",
  "response": "Actually, Amazon already has a significant logistics and delivery network:\n\n1. Amazon Logistics (Amazon's own delivery service)\n- Started in 2013\n- Operates in many countries\n- Handles a large portion of their own package deliveries\n- Reduces reliance on traditional carriers like UPS and FedEx\n\n2. Amazon Flex\n- A program where independent contractors can deliver Amazon packages using their personal vehicles\n- Provides flexible work opportunities\n- Helps expand delivery capacity\n\n3. Amazon Air\n- Their own air cargo network\n- Operates cargo planes to transport packages\n- Reduces dependency on other shipping companies\n\nSo in many ways, Amazon is already operating a courier business, primarily focused on supporting their own e-commerce operations but also increasingly serving third-party customers.\n\nTheir strategy seems to be gradually building out their own logistics infrastructure rather than competing directly with traditional courier services in a broad, generalized way.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these points?",
